<worksheet xml:id="notes-gr1information">
<title>Graphing Quadratics and Quadratic Models</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        For this outcome  Specifically, for this outcome, students should be able to:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Find the intercepts of a quadratic function.</p></li>
          <li><p>Find the vertex of a quadratic function.</p></li>
          <li><p>Find the axis of symmetry of a quadratic function.</p></li>
          <li>Rewrite a quadratic function in vertex form.</li>
          <li><p>Use a quadratic function to model real-world situations.</p></li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </introduction>
    <page>
      <p><alert>Quadratic Functions</alert></p>
      <p>A <term>quadratic function</term> is a function of the 
        form <m>f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c</m>, where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, 
        and <m>c</m> are constants and <m>a \ne 0</m>.</p>
      <p><alert>Vertex Form of a Quadratic Function</alert></p>
        <p>The vertex form of a quadratic function is given by 
          <m>f(x) = a(x - h)^2 + k</m>, where <m>(h, k)</m> is the 
          vertex of the parabola.</p>
        <p>One can convert a quadratic function from standard form 
          to vertex form by completing the square. To complete the square, we 
          first need to factor out the coefficient of <m>x^2</m> from the first 
          two terms of the function. We then take the coefficient of <m>x</m>, 
          divide it by 2, and square it. We then add and subtract this value 
          inside the function. The last step is to factor the perfect square trinomial.</p>  
        <p>The vertex of a parabola can also be found using the formula 
          <m>(h, k) = \left(-\frac{b}{2a}, f\left(-\frac{b}{2a}\right)\right)</m>.</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p><alert>Graphing Quadratics</alert></p>
      <p>To graph a quadratic function, we can use the vertex form of the function. 
        The vertex of the parabola is given by <m>(h, k)</m>. The axis of symmetry 
        is the vertical line <m>x = h</m>. The direction of opening is determined 
        by the sign of <m>a</m>. If <m>a \gt 0</m>, the parabola opens upward; if 
        <m>a \lt 0</m>, it opens downward.</p>
    </page>
    <page>
      <p><alert>Modeling Quadratic Functions</alert></p>
      <p>Modeling quadratic functions involves using quadratic equations to 
        represent real-world situations. For example, the height of a projectile 
        over time can be modeled by a quadratic function. The vertex of the parabola 
        represents the maximum or minimum value of the function, depending on whether 
        the parabola opens upward or downward.</p>
        <p>To model a situation with a quadratic function, we need to identify 
          the key features of the situation, such as the vertex, axis of symmetry, 
          and direction of opening. We can then use these features to write the equation 
          of the quadratic function that models the situation.</p>
        <p>Strategy for solving word problems:
            <ol>
              <li><p>Read and re-read the problem carefully.</p></li>
              <li><p>Identify what is being asked and what information is given.</p></li>
              <li><p>Define variables to represent the unknown quantities.</p></li>
              <li><p>Draw a diagram or use a table to organize the information.</p></li>
              <li><p>Determine if there is a formula that relates the known and unknown quantities.</p></li>
              <li><p>Form an equation based on the information and the formula.</p></li>
              <li><p>Solve the equation.</p></li>
              <li><p>Check the solution and interpret it in the context of the problem.</p></li>
            </ol>
          </p>
    </page>
  
</worksheet>
